{
  "texts": [
    "To achieve this, R2BERT combines both mean squared error and cross-entropy loss functions.",
    "The mean squared error, serving as the regression loss, ensures the accuracy of the score in each batch, while the cross-entropy loss, acting as the ranking loss, preserves the order within the batch.",
    "However, the order Although R2BERT demonstrated superior performance compared to convolutional and recurrent neural networks, it has several limitations: (1) batch-wise ranking overlooks global order information, (2) determining the appropriate weights to balance the loss functions for optimization, and (3) BERT only supports sequences of up to 512 tokens, leading to the truncation of longer essays.",
    "Xie et al. (2022) proposed a neural pairwise contrastive learning (NPCR) approach that addresses the issues with global ranking and weighting the objective functions.",
    "NPCR addresses these issues by introducing neural pairwise ranking instead of batch-wise ranking in order to capture rank information from the entire dataset."
  ]
}